        {
          "id": 29474,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Thromboxane Synthase</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 29475,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">5&rsquo; Nucleotidase</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">In a biochemistry class focused on enzyme inhibitors, the professor introduces the concept of &quot;suicidal enzymes,&quot; which essentially undergo self-deactivation during the catalysis of their reactions. She then presents a list of enzymes and asks the students to identify which enzyme fits the description of a &quot;suicidal enzyme.&quot; Which of the following enzymes is known to be a &quot;suicidal enzyme&quot;?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1873414",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30072,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B. </span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Cyclooxygenase</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Cyclooxygenase</strong> is a <strong>&lsquo;Suicide Enzyme&rsquo; </strong>because <strong>&lsquo;Switching off&rsquo; of prostaglandin activity</strong> is achieved by the <strong>self-catalyzed destruction property.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Cyclooxygenase (COX) / Prostaglandin H synthase: </span></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"margin-left:40px\">\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Involved in prostanoid (prostaglandin. Thromboxane and Prostacyclin) synthesis</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">This enzyme has two activities, a cyclooxygenase and peroxidase</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">COX is present as two isoenzymes, COX-1 and COX-2.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Drugs acting as inhibitors of COX: </span></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:40px; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">NSAID such as </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"margin-left:40px\">\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Aspirin (Inhibits COX-1 and COX-2)</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Indomethacin and ibuprofen (inhibit cyclooxygenases by competing with arachidonate)</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Coxibs (Selectively inhibit COX-2)</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:40px; text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Anti-inflammatory Corticosteroids</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A. Lipoxygenase:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This <strong>enzyme catalyzes</strong> the <strong>dioxygenation of polyunsaturated fatty acids in lipids.</strong> Although it participates in a reaction similar to that of COX, it is not commonly referred to as a suicidal enzyme.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C. Thromboxane Synthase:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This <strong>enzyme catalyzes</strong> the <strong>formation of thromboxane</strong> from <strong>prostaglandin H2</strong>, but it is not classified as a suicidal enzyme.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D. 5&rsquo; Nucleotidase:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This <strong>enzyme hydrolyzes phosphate groups</strong> from <strong>nucleotides</strong> and is not classified as a suicidal enzyme.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Cyclooxygenase</strong> (COX) is often referred to as a <strong>&quot;suicidal enzyme&quot; </strong>because it <strong>permanently alters its active site</strong> during the process of <strong>converting arachidonic acid</strong> to <strong>prostaglandin H2,</strong> which eventually leads to the <strong>production of prostaglandin</strong>s. The term &quot;suicidal enzyme&quot; is attributed to the fact that these enzymes undergo a one-time, self-destructive catalytic cycle after which they are no longer functional.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Harper 30/e p241.</span></span></strong></p>",
