      "id": 7379,
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 29484,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Can incorporate 2 atoms of O2 in a substance</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 29485,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Can incorporate 1 atom of O2 in a substance</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 29486,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Important in hydroxylation of steroids</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 29487,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Catalysed carboxylation of drugs</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 60-year-old man with a history of chronic steroid use for rheumatoid arthritis presents with altered liver enzymes. Given his medication history, the physician is concerned about the impact on hepatic enzyme functions, especially those involved in steroid metabolism. Which enzyme characteristic is least associated with steroid metabolism in this patient&#39;s liver?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3621142",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30073,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. D. </span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Catalysed carboxylation of drugs</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Carboxylation reactions</strong>, which involve the addition of a <strong>carboxyl group to a molecule,</strong> are <strong>not typically associated </strong>with the <strong>hepatic metabolism of steroids</strong>. <strong>Steroid metabolism</strong> primarily involves <strong>reactions such as hydroxylation, </strong>which is <strong>facilitated by enzymes</strong> <strong>capable</strong> of <strong>incorporating oxygen atoms </strong>into the <strong>steroid molecule.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> A. Incorporation of two oxygen atoms into substrates:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Dioxygenases</strong> can <strong>incorporate two oxygen atoms from O2 </strong>into substrates. While important in some metabolic pathways, this activity is less common in the direct metabolism of steroids by the liver.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> B. Hydroxylation of steroids:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This is a <strong>key reaction in the metabolism of steroids</strong>, involving the <strong>addition of an OH group</strong>. Enzymes like cytochrome P450s, which incorporate one oxygen atom into the substrate, often facilitate this reaction.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> C. Incorporation of one oxygen atom into substrates:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This describes the <strong>activity of monooxygenases,</strong> such as those in the <strong>cytochrome P450 family, </strong>which are crucial for the hydroxylation of steroids in the liver.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Oxygenases</strong> can be <strong>monooxygenase or dioxygenase.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Monooxygenase </strong>can <strong>incorporate 1 atom of oxygen molecule</strong> to the <strong>substrate.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Dioxygenase can incorporate both the atoms of oxygen molecules to the substrate.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Phase 1 Xenobiotic reactions such as <strong>hydroxylation</strong> is catalysed mainly by members of a class of enzymes known as monooxygenases or cytochrome P450s.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Harper 30/e p118, 119.</span></span></strong></p>",
