      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A medical toxicologist is consulting on the case of a patient who has been exposed to a significant amount of an environmental toxin. The toxicologist is discussing the body&#39;s natural mechanisms for detoxification and the substances involved in these processes. The patient&#39;s family, concerned and eager to understand, asks about substances in the body that aid in detoxification. The toxicologist provides a list but includes one substance that is not typically involved in detoxification. Which of the following substances is NOT typically a detoxifying agent in the human body?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3492596",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30071,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. D) Glycogen</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Glycogen </strong>is the primary <strong>storage</strong> form of <strong>glucose</strong> in the body, particularly in the<strong> liver and muscle cells, </strong>and is <strong>not</strong> directly involved in <strong>detoxification processes.</strong> It <strong>serves </strong>as an <strong>energy reserve </strong>rather than a <strong>detoxifying agent.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A. Glycine:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Glycine is involved in the<strong> conjugation</strong> of various substances, including <strong>bile acids, benzoate, and salicylates</strong>, as part of <strong>detoxification pathways,</strong> especially in the <strong>liver.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">. <strong>Glutathione:</strong></span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Glutathione is a crucial <strong>antioxidant</strong> in cells and plays a significant role in <strong>detoxifying harmful compounds</strong> by <strong>conjugation and reducing oxidative stress.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C. Glucuronic acid:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Glucuronic acid is used in the<strong> conjugation</strong> of various <strong>drugs and toxins </strong>in the liver, making them more <strong>water-soluble </strong>and <strong>easier to excrete</strong> in the<strong> urine.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Phase two reactions are conjugation reactions</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> involves </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/12/screenshot-2024-04-12-152218.png\" style=\"height:303px; width:1000px\" /></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Glycine&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">and<strong> glutamine</strong> can also act as<strong> conjugating agents.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: DM Vasudevan 9/e: p 480,481.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
