      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">In a discussion on the detoxification pathways for foreign compounds (xenobiotics), a toxicologist outlines the two main phases of biotransformation. The group is then tasked with identifying which of the following reactions is not typically categorized as part of Phase II xenobiotic metabolism:</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1150530",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30070,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C) Hydroxylation</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Hydroxylation </strong>is a reaction that typically falls under <strong>Phase I of xenobiotic metabolism</strong>, where the introduction of a <strong>hydroxyl group </strong>into a <strong>compound </strong>makes it <strong>more polar </strong>and often prepares it for further <strong>modification in Phase II</strong>. <strong>Phase I reactions </strong>involve the functionalization of the <strong>xenobiotic</strong>, while <strong>Phase II reactions </strong>generally involve <strong>conjugation</strong>, where the <strong>modified compound </strong>from <strong>Phase I </strong>is <strong>linked </strong>with <strong>another substance </strong>to <strong>increase solubility </strong>and <strong>facilitate excretion</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A.</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> This is a <strong>common Phase II reaction </strong>where a <strong>glucuronic acid group </strong>is added to a <strong>xenobiotic</strong>, <strong>increasing its solubility </strong>for <strong>excretion</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B.</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> In <strong>sulfation</strong>, a <strong>sulfate group </strong>is added to a <strong>xenobiotic during Phase II metabolism</strong>, <strong>enhancing </strong>its <strong>water solubility.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D.</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Methylation </strong>involves the addition of a <strong>methyl group to a xenobiotic </strong>and is considered a <strong>conjugation reaction</strong>, placing it in the <strong>category of Phase II metabolism.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Phase two </strong>reactions are <strong>conjugation reactions</strong>: a molecule <strong>normally present in the body </strong>is added to the<strong> reactive site </strong>of the <strong>phase one metabolite.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/18/screenshot-2024-04-18-131308.png\" style=\"height:317px; width:1000px\" /></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Conjugation</strong> with <strong>Glycine, glutathione and glutamine</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Acetylation</span></span></span></strong></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Methylation Reactions</span></span></span></strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: DM Vasudevan 9/e: p 480</span></strong></span></span></p>",
